XML_CASESUMMARY.SUMMARY:
This single vehicle crash occurred in a rural area on a physically divided asphalt highway consisting of two northbound and two southbound lanes that are divided by a concrete jersey barrier topped by a chain-link fence. The roadway is straight and downhill for northbound traffic, has rumble strips and a full paved shoulder to the right of the travel lanes and a narrow paved partial shoulder to the left of the travel lanes. The posted speed limit for the highway is 89 kmph (55 mph). At the time of this late afternoon crash, the weather was clear and the road surface was dry and free of defects.
Vehicle one (V1), a 1991 Toyota 4 Runner SR5, was northbound in lane #1 when, for unknown reasons, the V1 driver applied brakes with full lockup and V1 entered a counterclockwise rotation, crossed the number 2 lane then departed the road to the left, and impacted the barrier with its front plane. V1 continued to rotate counterclockwise, re-contacted the barrier with the back plane, began to rollover to the left as a result of contact to the barrier and tripping forces to the left side tires, and slid to final rest on its top after rolling over 2 quarter turns. V1 came to final rest on its roof facing generally north in the number one lane. V1 was towed due to damage.
The V1 driver, a 22-year-old male, was not licensed, carried only a passport as identification and did not speak English, according to the police report. There were two other occupants in the vehicle at the time of the crash. None of the occupants could be located or contacted. V1's speed was reported only as above the speed limit of 89 kmph (55 mph). Pre-crash skid-marks start out in a straight pattern in lane one then continue in a yaw pattern towards the center divider. This physical evidence suggests that the V1 driver may have been trying to avoid another vehicle or animal entering the roadway from the right; however, this could not be ascertained. Without further information the exact reason for the driver applying the brakes cannot be determined. There were no known vehicle or environmental pre-crash factors for V1.
The Critical Pre-crash Event for V1 was coded as: this vehicle control loss due to, unknown cause of control loss. The Critical Reason for the Critical Event was coded as a driver related factor, type of driver error unknown.
